[1
Date: Tue, 08 Jun 1999 01:13:13 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media (edited) 7 Jun 1999

South Korea, Hong Kong, Singapore and Japan all acted at the end of last
week to ban or increase checks on some imported European food.
Taiwan said on Monday it was planning to ban dairy products imported from
Belgium and France, while Thailand said it was likely to target Belgian
products soon. Shoppers in Singapore were forced to seek alternatives to
European brands of baby formula, after most brands were recalled from
supermarkets following a ban on European dairy products.
The dioxin issue has been a hot topic in Japan for most of this year amid
concerns that rubbish incinerators were emitting the carcinogen and dioxin
may have contaminated vegetables.
Malaysia, which has been reeling from a viral epidemic that has killed more
than 100 people and devastated its own pork industry, imposed a temporary
ban on EU food imports on Monday. The ban covered all meat, eggs and
egg-based foods and dairy products, the Bernama news agency quoted Health
Minister Chua Jui Meng as saying.
*******
[2
Date: Tue, 08 Jun 1999 01:13:13 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media (edited) 7 Jun 1999

Bulgaria has banned imports of fodder, meat and dairy and poultry products
from Belgium, France and the Netherlands fearing the goods could be
contaminated with toxic chemical dioxin, the National Veterinary Service
said.
"The ban is imposed and it includes imports of all products of animal
origin and feed from Belgium, France and Holland and German chickens and
eggs," NVS deputy executive director Yanko Ivanov told Reuters on Monday.
"The ban is temporary but it will remain effective until the EU resolves
the issue," said Ivanov.
******
[3
Date: Tue, 8 Jun 1999
From: Chan Yow Cheong <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: Bangkok Post, 8 Jun 1999 [edited

The Public Health Ministry yesterday slapped a ban on import and sale of
dairy products from Belgium amid a contamination scare. The ban, prompted
by reports of contamination by dioxin, a carcinogen, is effective today and
the goods affected include dairy products, meat and eggs.
Though the FDA [Thailand's Food and Drug Administration has three
importers registered for bringing animal meat into the country, so far none
have done so, said [Mongkhol na Songkhla, the FDA secretary-general. In
May, about two million baht worth of white egg, which is used as a food
ingredient, was imported from Belgium, he said. Currently, the FDA has 16
importers of Belgian products registered, of which 10 are of chocolates,
two of biscuits.
Dr Mongkhol said the main concern is the recent import of white egg, but
the importers have confirmed the product is not sold within the country. It
is exported to a third country as a food ingredient.

