[5
Date: Wed, 09 Jun 1999 07:01:29 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media (edited) 9 Jun 1999

DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC OF THE CONGO:The Democratic Republic of the Congo has
banned imports of chicken meat and eggs from former colonial power Belgium
following the scare over contamination of animal feed there with the toxic
chemical dioxin. The government announced the ban in a statement issued on
Tuesday and said that all suspect food would be withdrawn from the market
for analysis.
THE NETHERLANDS: The Netherlands' central bureau for food retail (CBL)
has ordered shops to withdraw 519 Belgian products in case they contain
cancer-causing dioxin, Dutch NOS radio reported Wednesday.
It said the list of brands, published by the CBL Wednesday morning,
included meat, cheese and other dairy products. Products on the list
include some processed cheeses, meats, chocolate products, snacks, cakes,
biscuits and dog food.
The CBL had decided to order the withdrawal of the products because the
suppliers had failed to give sufficient assurances that they did not
contain dioxin, the report said.
SOUTH AFRICA:(Source: Business Day(edited)- The names of Belgian farms from
which contaminated meat could have been imported since January would be
released in SA, the agriculture department's food safety director, Gideon
Bruckner, said yesterday.
This follows the worldwide ban at the weekend of imports of poultry, pork,
beef and dairy products from Belgium after it was found that the products,
especially poultry and pork, contained toxins which posed a serious health
threat to the public.
Scientists found dangerously high levels of dioxin, a toxic chemical linked
to cancer, in the meat of animals raised on 13 Belgium farms. "The dioxin
on these farms has been traced to a small amount of combustion oil
incorporated into feed at a food manufacturing plant," Bruckner said.
